{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}} {{for|the Australian politician|Charles Metz (Australian politician)}} {{Infobox officeholder |honorific-prefix = |name = Charles Gérard Emmanuel Metz |honorific-suffix = |image = Charles Metz.JPG |alt = |caption = |office1 = [[President of the Chamber of Deputies of Luxembourg|President]] of the [[Chamber of Deputies of Luxembourg|Chamber of Deputies]] |term_start1 = 1848 |term_end1 = 1853 |office2 = Member of the [[Chamber of Deputies of Luxembourg|Chamber of Deputies]] for [[Luxembourg-Campagne (Chamber of Deputies of Luxembourg constituency)|Luxembourg-Campagne]] |term_start2 = 1848 |term_end2 = 1853 |birth_date = 6 January 1799 |birth_place = [[Luxembourg City]] |death_date = 24 April 1853 |death_place = [[Diekirch]] |restingplace = |restingplacecoordinates = |nationality = Luxembourgian |party = |otherparty = |spouse = |children = |residence = |alma_mater = |occupation = Journalist |religion = |signature = |signature_alt = |footnotes = }} '''Charles Gérard Emmanuel Metz''' (6 January 1799 – 24 April 1853) was a Luxembourgian politician, journalist, and lawyer. He was a prominent pro-Belgian in the [[Belgian Revolution]], serving in the Belgian national legislature, before entering the [[Chamber of Deputies of Luxembourg|Chamber of Deputies]] of Luxembourg, of which he was the first [[President of the Chamber of Deputies of Luxembourg|President]], from 1848 to 1853.
Charles was born in [[Luxembourg City]] in 1799 to Jean Metz and Anne-Marie-Justine Gérard. He studied at the [[Athénée de Luxembourg]] and the [[lycée]] in [[Metz]], [[France]], before reading law at the newly established [[University of Liège]], graduating in 1822.<ref>Mersch (1963), p. 429</ref> Metz first became politically active as a pro-Belgian spokesperson during the [[Belgian Revolution]]. In the [[National Congress of Belgium|National Congress]] called in [[Brussels]], Metz was one of sixteen [[deputy (legislator)|deputies]] representing the [[Arrondissements of Belgium|arrondissement]] of Luxembourg (claimed in its entirety by Belgium).<ref name="Mersch 430">Mersch (1963), p. 430</ref> In 1836, Metz moved to [[Arlon]], where he established a newspaper, ''L'Echo de Luxembourg'', to promote Luxembourgian and liberal interests, along with [[Emmanuel Servais]] and [[Victor Tesch]].<ref name="Mersch 430" /><ref>Mersch (1963), p. 373</ref>
In 1837, Metz was elected to the [[Chamber of Representatives of Belgium|Chamber of Representatives]], representing [[Grevenmacher (district)|Grevenmacher]] until 1841.<ref name="Mersch 430" /> He urged the Belgians to enter negotiations with the [[Netherlands]], but spoke against the [[Third Partition of Luxembourg]], ultimately voting against the [[Treaty of London (1839)|Treaty of London]].<ref name="Mersch 432">Mersch (1963), p. 432</ref> In 1839, he stood for election to the Chamber of Representatives for [[Bastogne]], but lost, remaining as representative of now-partitioned Grevenmacher.<ref name="Mersch 432" />
Metz, along with his younger brothers [[Auguste Metz|Auguste]] and [[Norbert Metz|Norbert]], establish the steel company ''Auguste Metz & Cie'' in 1838, but he played little active role in its operations.<ref name="Mersch 432" /> Metz was allowed to return to the (smaller) Grand Duchy of Luxembourg to practise law in 1842.<ref>Mersch (1963), p. 433</ref> With the collapse of the [[Orangism (Luxembourg)|Orangist]] ''Journal de la Ville et du Pays Luxembourg'' in 1844, Metz went about establishing the new ''Courrier de Luxembourg'', along with his brother Norbert and other leading liberals, as well as the conservative [[Orangism (Luxembourg)|Orangist]] [[Mathieu-Lambert Schrobilgen]], with whom the ideological split became more and more apparent over time.<ref name="Mersch 434">Mersch (1963), p. 434</ref>
During 1848, Metz was elected to the [[Constituent Assembly of Luxembourg|Constituent Assembly]], being elected to represent the [[Cantons of Luxembourg|cantons]] of [[Esch-sur-Alzette (Chamber of Deputies constituency)|Esch]] and [[Luxembourg (Chamber of Deputies constituency)|Luxembourg]], but opting to represent the latter.<ref name="Mersch 434" /> The Metz brothers narrowly failed to defer Luxembourg sending a delegation from Luxembourg to the [[Frankfurt Parliament]],<ref>Mersch (1963), p. 436</ref> although their position cost them their potential part in the three-man delegation.<ref>Mersch (1963), p. 436–7</ref> The Metz brothers were elected to the inaugural [[Chamber of Deputies of Luxembourg|Chamber of Deputies]]. Charles was elected the first [[President of the Chamber of Deputies of Luxembourg|President of the Chamber]], which he remained until his death on 24 April 1853.<ref>Mersch (1963), p. 440</ref><ref>Mersch (1963), p. 446</ref>
He married Justine Vannérus on 26 December 1827 in [[Diekirch]]. Vannérus died in 1849, by which time they had seven children, of whom three (Jules, Irma, and Léonie) survived to adulthood.<ref>Mersch (1963), p. 319</ref> Metz's only son, Jules, followed his father at the ''Courrier'', and then into the Chamber of Deputies for [[Capellen (Chamber of Deputies constituency)|Capellen]].<ref>Mersch (1963), p. 320</ref> Léonie married the [[Jersey]]-born engineer [[Edmond Le Gallais]].<ref>Mersch (1963), p. 328</ref>
